Question - What is Arrays?
Answer -
• An array is a collection or group of similar data types.
• It stores elements in contiguous memory locations.
• Arrays are objects of the base type System.Array.
• Arrays are static in nature, meaning their size is fixed once declared.
• The index of an array starts from 0 and ends at (n - 1), where n is the total number of elements.
• Arrays are useful when you want to store a fixed set of values of the same type in a single variable.

🔹 Declaration examples:
i) int[] data = { 10, 20, 30, 40, 5, 60, 70, 5, 9 };
ii) int[] a = new int[] { 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80 };
iii) int[] a = new int[3];
     a[0] = 10;
     a[1] = 20;
     a[2] = 30;

• In short, arrays help to manage multiple values of the same type efficiently by accessing them through indices(index pural).

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Question - How many types of arrays are there?
Answer -

• In C#, there are mainly two types of arrays based on dimensions:
   i) Single Dimensional Array (1D)
   ii) Multi Dimensional Array (2D or more)
 iii)Jagged Array

🔹 1) Single Dimensional Array:
• Also known as a linear array.
• Stores elements in a single row.
• Example:
  int[] numbers = { 10, 20, 30, 40 };

🔹 2) Multi Dimensional Array:
• Stores elements in table format (rows and columns).
• Commonly used as a 2D array.
• Example:
  int[,] matrix = {
      {1, 2, 3},
      {4, 5, 6}
  };

🔹 3) Jagged Array (Array of Arrays):
• An array in which each element is itself an array.
• The inner arrays can have different lengths.
• Example:
  int[][] jagged = new int[2][];
  jagged[0] = new int[] { 1, 2 };
  jagged[1] = new int[] { 3, 4, 5 };

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Question - What is Single Dimensional Array?
Answer -

• A Single Dimensional Array (1D array) stores elements in a single row using contiguous memory locations.

Key Points:
i) Elements are stored in one continuous line in memory.
ii) Indexing starts from 0 and goes up to (n - 1), where n is the total number of elements.

🔹 Example 1: Basic Array Access

using System;
namespace Array
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            string[] a = new string[4];
            a[0] = "Alok";
            a[1] = "Vikas";
            a[2] = "Surya";
            a[3] = "Sunil";

            Console.WriteLine(a[0]);  // Output: Alok
            Console.WriteLine(a[1]);  // Output: Vikas
            Console.WriteLine(a[2]);  // Output: Surya
            Console.WriteLine(a[3]);  // Output: Sunil
        }
    }
}

🔹 Example 2: Using for loop

using System;
namespace Array
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            int[] numbers = { 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60 };

            for (int i = 0; i < numbers.Length; i++)
            {
                Console.WriteLine(numbers[i]);
            }

            Console.ReadLine();
        }
    }
}

Output:
10  
20  
30  
40  
50  
60

